Russia and Turkey: An Alliance of the “Incompatible”?
It was a gesture that ended the crisis.
The leaders of Russia and Turkey met on Tuesday to shake hands and announce a formal end to an eight-month-long verbal war and economic sanctions.
But while Vladimir Putin welcomed the Turkish counterpart in the sumptuous hall of the palace in St. Petersburg, I had the impression that Ankara wanted more of this reconciliation.
There was a handshake, yes.
But Putin did not smile and barely radiated warmth, even by his aloof standards.
Recep Tayyip Erdogan, on the other hand, has repeatedly spoken about his "dear friend" Mr Putin - five times, as one of the reports states.
I didn't count it.
He also promised that relations with Russia will not only return to their pre-crisis level, but will be even better.
The next day, a local newspaper reported that Erdogan acted as if nothing bad had ever happened.
I think his enthusiasm revealed the exact opposite.
But the persistent cold emanating from Putin showed that the Russian leader had forgotten nothing.
The real cause of the crisis was the first thing he mentioned in his opening speech: the downing of a Russian fighter jet by Turkey on the Syrian border.
Moscow’s reaction was furious.
Putin punched around and accused Ankara of stabbing Moscow in the back.
The scandal was all the greater because it came from an imaginary friend.
Rebuilding true trust will be difficult, perhaps even impossible.
Russian public opinion has also changed since December.
The state-controlled media has waged a massive nationwide campaign against Ankara for months.
It was as if the Turks were responsible for everything.
More serious were allegations from top officials that Erdogan’s own family benefited from the illegal oil trade in parts of Syria controlled by the so-called Islamic State.
He strongly denied this.
But in St. Petersburg, the official message came that it was time to move on.
After all, this meeting only happened because Putin got the apology he demanded from President Erdogan.
Russia could have declared such a victory.
For Ankara, the benefits of a ceasefire are clear.
In the first place, Erdogan was almost stripped of power last month during a failed coup and therefore needs all his friends.
Repeated terrorist attacks in Turkey have also visibly shaken him.
There is also an economic motive.
Russia's sanctions have had a harsh impact - notably the cancellation of charter flights that transport several million Russian tourists to the coast of Turkey each year.
This number has decreased by almost 90%.
As far as Russia is concerned, tour operators and charter companies will certainly take a breather when flights are resumed.
They earn on Mediterranean tourism at the end of the season.
Even this week, state television promised cheaper fruit and vegetables when imports of agricultural commodities from Turkey are allowed again.
"Tourists there, tomatoes back here," as reported in the Vedemosti newspaper.
But the visit had additional political value for Moscow.
Ankara is angry at the West for what it sees as a poor response to the coup attempt.
In addition, the long-standing animosity of the protracted talks on joining the EU and the entry of Putin - who is eager to take advantage of the cooling and sever Turkey's ties with the West.
The Russian leader certainly earned bonus points when Ankara asked him for help from the elected authorities after the coup attempt.
You have to understand that for Moscow, which has a deep-seated fear of regime change, this is a given.
So the summit at this pompous, seaside palace has allowed Russia and Turkey to demonstrate what one analyst has described to me as “an alliance of the incompatibles”: how the forces of two countries that feel rejected and exploited by the West are joining forces.
However, despite the fact that they have publicly shown mutual reconciliation, there are fundamental differences between the two countries.
The first is Syria, where Moscow recently took the role of a peacemaker, but where Russia and Turkey stand on opposite sides.
It could be said that after nearly three hours of initial talks, the two presidents said in a press conference that they had not even mentioned the issue.
The Turkish president deliberately avoided answering the question about the differences between them, while Putin chose to highlight these differences.
There is no clear agreement on the basis of which the two countries can find common ground on the issue of Syria.
But after months of open hostility - and given the risk of total disaster when a NATO member shot down a Russian fighter jet - it is certainly better that the two leaders at least talk to each other again.
