French Court Refuses to Demolish Shops at Jungle Refugee Camp
A court in France has rejected an order by authorities in Calais to demolish dozens of makeshift shops and restaurants in the jungle camp, where thousands of refugees live.
During a court hearing this week, authorities in Calais objected that the state should be able to cancel a total of 72 makeshift shops where people inside the camp sell goods, from cigarettes to energy drinks, offer haircuts, in makeshift restaurants sell tea for 50 cents or basic dishes for several euros.
The prefect's office in Calais argued that the sites needed to be demolished because they represented a parallel economy that did not pay taxes and because they posed fire hazards and health risks.
Humanitarian organizations have said in court that shops and restaurants are vital and that free meals offered by state-sponsored associations and other groups do not provide a food supplement for the growing numbers of refugees in the camp.
Disputed makeshift shops and restaurants often provide shelter and free food to people in need.
A court in Lille ruled that there was no legal basis to prevent people from running 72 makeshift stores, but said that Calais's objections were "completely understandable".
Judge Jean-Francois Molla said that grocery stores, cafes and restaurants have a much bigger role to play than simply serving food to people who “live in extremely dire conditions.”
He said the premises provide peaceful places to meet refugees and volunteers.
One site threatened with demolition was a cafe in the camp, Jungle Book Kids, run by a non-profit organization that offers 200 meals a day, hours of English and French, and asylum counseling for hundreds of unaccompanied minors at risk in the camp.
More than 170,000 people have signed a petition to protect the children’s café.
The Guardian received a letter saying the closure of the café would be “a disaster for these children, some as young as 8 years old.”
Help Refugees and L’Auberge des Migrants estimated on Friday that the refugee numbers in the camp had risen to more than 9,000 over the summer, the highest ever.
