Compared to the French, you are not negative, says a Muslim living in Prague.
You come from France.
Where did you live before moving to Prague?
My parents are originally from Algeria.
I was born in the south of France, near the Spanish border.
I've moved around quite a bit.
I lived in Toulouse, Lyon and Marseille.
I studied journalism in France, which led me to work in a magazine.
Why did you decide to move out of the country?
I was starting to feel like I was suffocating in France.
I just didn't want to live there anymore.
Mainly because of the atmosphere.
I thought every Frenchman was negative.
People in France are negative in general, but things have gotten worse lately.
It’s interesting that you mention negativity.
This is how some people view the Czech character.
You are not negative compared to the French.
Some people may not feel that way when they come to France because they don’t see it as tourists.
But it was too much for me.
A big issue is money.
People feel that they have little money, but the minimum wage in France is fifteen hundred euros, which I think is enough.
Now there is a problem with the behavior of people towards Muslims.
That's completely incomprehensible to me.
For example, in the street where I lived, my non-Muslim neighbor started looking down on me just because I was Muslim.
Like I'm some kind of evil.
That's why I didn't feel well in France.
My family stayed there.
So you decided to go to another country.
Why did you choose the Czech Republic?
I was looking for a job basically anywhere else and I came across a vacancy with Air France here in Prague.
I have to admit that I didn’t know about Prague at the beginning.
I knew something about the Czech Republic, my father even told me about what was happening in Czechoslovakia, but I did not know what to expect from Prague.
I've been here for three years now, and I can't imagine not living here.
Was it a big difference when you moved from France to Prague?
Mostly because of a different atmosphere.
Maybe it's because I don't speak Czech, so I can't catch any negative reactions or swearing, but I feel like people are more free here.
That I could do anything, dress any way, and no one would judge me.
In France, someone is always looking at you in a bad way, for example, when you have special clothes and things like that.
In Prague, I started to feel really free.
I don't think that's the kind of thing that Prague people care about.
Where do you work now?
After working at Air France, I worked for a travel website for a while.
Then, with another friend, we set up a website where people offer and search for shared housing.
So far, we only operate in Prague, but we would like to extend it to the whole of Central Europe.
Do you have any Czech friends in Prague?
I have two very close friends here, who are half Czech, and two more Czech friends.
I have to say that another peculiarity of the Czechs is that they keep their distance at first.
They won't let anyone near their body right away.
This is quite different from where I grew up.
In the south, everyone hugs and kisses on the cheek.
It's different here, but I understand it's a cultural thing, so I'm trying to adapt.
You mentioned that you don’t speak Czech.
Is the language barrier a problem for you?
On the contrary, I have it quite simple in Prague, because perhaps everyone here speaks English.
Even at bedtime or at the grocery store.
I would like to learn Czech, but I don’t have that much time.
And since everyone can communicate at least a little in English, I do not have such a need to learn the language quickly.
And every time I have a problem, there's someone who can help me.
Have you experienced any negative reactions?
Is it because you are Muslim?
Not really.
Perhaps it is also because I work in an international environment that is more tolerant.
One experience comes to mind.
My manager, a Czech, once told me about a French football team and said something like this: They’re not French, they’re Africans.
I'm quite touched by that.
But if anyone has a problem with me being a Muslim, that hasn't happened to me yet.
This is despite the fact that a colleague once warned me about some anti-Muslim demonstrations.
He told me not to go downtown, they'd call me names.
Anti-Muslim demonstrations are partly linked to terrorist attacks.
How does the current situation affect you?
Are you afraid that something similar could happen in Paris, Nice or Brussels?
I feel safe in Prague.
But the problem is, anything can happen anywhere these days.
Until recently, I couldn’t imagine something like this happening in France.
This is not just about Muslims.
Islam does not recognize violence.
For me, the people who kill are not Muslims.
The Koran says that man has no right to kill because he is not God.
How do you feel when terrorists shield themselves from your beliefs?
It's very hard.
I feel shame and guilt, even though I shouldn't feel it at all.
I try not to watch the violence stories too much, but every time I read something, I feel the need to apologize for something that isn't really my fault.
I'm a completely different person, so why should I apologize for terrorists?
We met on the square of Jiřího z Poděbrad.
On Wednesday, Czech Muslims and Christians demonstrated against the violence.
Did you register it?
I didn't know about that.
But the way I see it, these people feel the need to prove that they don't agree with violence.
I don't think they'd have to do anything like that.
Why should they feel guilty for something they didn't cause?
Do you meet other Muslims in Prague?
My colleagues are from Egypt and other Muslim countries, for example.
They are a little more religious than I am, so sometimes we have quite wild discussions about Islam, because we all perceive it a little differently.
I come from France, so I went through a different education, for example, they learned Islam in school.
We have different approaches, but we respect each other.
People sometimes associate Islam with the subordinate status of a woman.
How do you see it?
I don't feel submissive at all.
Quite the opposite.
I'm a woman, I have strength.
It also means that you don’t have to wear a head covering.
Like the hijab?
And the way I've been raised is what makes it so special.
My mother, for example, is a true Muslim.
He prays five times a day, but he just doesn't wear a scarf.
She always taught me that faith is a purely personal thing.
It depends on how everyone interprets it.
When you read the Koran, you should make up your own mind about these things.
So when I read a passage in the Qur'an that says that God told the Prophet to hide his wives from the eyes of others, I said to myself: I am not the Prophet's wife, so why should I hide?
On the other hand, I respect that, and if I come to Iran or Saudi Arabia, for example, where headscarves are required, I will wear it.
Are you planning to stay in Prague?
For now, yes.
I didn't feel so good anywhere else.
I was thinking about Poland for a while, but I feel great in Prague.
I can even imagine raising my own children here.
Prague is the ideal city for this.
