Depressed food from a time of crisis - in "Square Meal"
Shortly after taking office in March 1933, Franklin Delano Roosevelt sat in the Oval Office and had lunch.
The gourmet President Roosevelt enjoyed selected dishes from 5th Avenue, such as goose liver pate and Maryland tortoise soup.
But his menu for the day was more modest: devil-like eggs in tomato sauce, potato puree, and plum pudding for dessert.
“It was an act of culinary solidarity with the people who suffered,” said Jane Ziegelman.
Her husband Andrew Coe added, "It was also a message to Americans how to eat."
The couple, who live in Brooklyn Heights, are dedicated to gastronomic history.
Andrew Coe’s last book, Chop Suey, was about Chinese cuisine in America, while Jane tells the life story of a house on the Lower East Side through food in her book 97 Orchard.
Their new work, A Square Meal, will be published Tuesday by Harper, is a history of American cuisine during the Great Depression.
They themselves showed culinary solidarity and met with a reporter for dinner at Eisenberg's sandwich shop, a small austere buffet in the Flatiron district, which has been in operation since the crisis, since 1929.
Jane (54) ordered cream cheese and a sandwich with chopped olives, Andrew (57) ordered turkey, mashed potatoes and mixed vegetables.
The reporter ordered a meatball, which the couple said was perfect for talking about food during a crisis.
"The burgers were very popular," said Miss Ziegelman.
It sold peanut, liver, and bean burgers.
They were made from the ingredients and other cheap foods that set the ingredients.
Imagine the amount of peanuts you would have to eat for dinner.
Andrew Coe grinned.
"They would be lying in your stomach like lead," he said.
In the years before the crisis, American cuisine, especially in rural areas, was served in the form of a buffet of what you eat.
Teams of women cooked for the farm workers, and a freshly baked cake was served for breakfast, lunch, and dinner.
It was the Americans who sent food to starving Europeans during the First World War. “A Square Meal” observes the ways in which the nation coped with the fact that it was suddenly not a land of plenty.
“It was a time when food became a central, feared point for the American people,” Coe said, explaining why he and his wife decided to write about it.
Equally feared was the new budget diet: Mysterious dishes such as meatballs and casserole dishes, casseroles as a "wonderful way to use up leftovers," Ziegelman noted, as cooks could hide unaesthetic ingredients under a layer of creamy sauce.
Fresh fruit has been replaced by cheaper dried fruit.
Meat - the focal point of American food for years - has become an economical luxury.
The strange blends, which were supposed to serve as a caloric and nutritional filling, took precedence over taste or even common sense when cooking.
During surveys for a book that contains recipes, Miss Ziegelman prepared a period dish of baked onion stuffed with peanut butter.
"It wasn't a favorite addition to the evening table," said Andrew Coe.
Jane Ziegelman said, “It was surreal.”
Peanut butter and roasted onions don't go together.
It was typical of a lot of homemade recipes.
As never before and never since, domestic economists - among them Louise Stanley, the head of the Federal Bureau of Home Economics from 1923 to 1943 - have governed the country's eating habits.
They published recipes and articles in newspapers and magazines, urged women to take over the reins of the budget, and turned tassels such as cream spaghetti with carrots into tasty dishes.
The book "A Square Meal" is a celebration of historical delicacies.
In particular, desserts were created in the government’s response to its hungry citizens, such as President Herbert Hoover’s “I’ll have a pie” pose.
While publicly praising the simple Iowa farm kitchen of his childhood, he dined as the select millionaire he became.
“He liked to eat continental cuisine, like fish with cucumber sauce,” said Andrew Coe.
He was eating in an almost gilded room, wearing a tuxedo.
He was incredibly old-fashioned.
President Roosevelt would probably have made the same mistake if his wife Eleanor hadn't made him lead by example with his own stomach.
As the book narrates, Mrs. Roosevelt hired a housekeeper who was not at all interested in the taste. This resulted in the White House “not only being served almost the bleakest dish in all of Washington, but also being prepared in the most dismal way.”
Many of the food habits of the crisis subsided as soon as the country got back on its feet.
The legacy has remained in our constant exploration of calories and nutritional values, says Ms. Ziegelman, and in the way science is applied to cooking.
The couple say they had a better understanding of Miss Ziegelman’s mother’s eating habits while writing the book, such as why she couldn’t throw away the food.
“She was really worried about wasting food,” Andrew Coe said.
Ziegelman said, “People were sick of her.”
There's been an accident with the wreaths.
When Eisenberg's tables were clear, she and Mr. Coe pulled out a dessert they had made at home: a plum dessert that President Roosevelt had eaten for lunch.
“It’s called plum cream,” Ziegelman said, adding that the usual trick was to give modest recipes elegant names.
There was no cream, just plums, some flour, sugar, water and cinnamon.
Everyone reluctantly plunged the spoon into a thick brown mass.
Surprisingly, it was wrong.
Andrew Coe joined in, and then again.
And like a good housekeeper, he said to his wife, "You could use a little chopped walnuts."
