NASA climate model: Venus was once habitable
According to NASA’s new climate model, Venus was once habitable.
Scientists at NASA’s Goddard Institute for Space Studies have developed a model for exploring Venus using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climate scientists.
The model was designed to determine whether conditions similar to those on Earth once existed on Venus, whose surface is hot, waterless, and saturated with CO2.
Scientists have previously suggested that Venus’s low rotational speed can be explained by its dense atmosphere.
However, according to the latest simulations, Venus may have once boasted a thin Earth-like atmosphere while rotating slowly.
The model also dealt with the earlier topography of Venus.
The planet probably had areas that were drier than Earth’s, but there was once enough water and geographic diversity to rule life and provide protection against rapid evaporation.
Previously, Venus also used the Sun, which was 30 percent dimmer.
“In a simulation of the GISS Venus during slow rotation, it exposes its daytime side to the sun for almost two months at a time,” said Anthony Del Genio, a scientist at GISS.
This heats the surface and creates rain, which creates a dense layer of clouds that behave like an umbrella and shield the surface from too much solar heat.
The result is a climate with average temperatures that are actually slightly lower than currently on Earth.
The model compiled a story of Venus similar to an evolution previously hypothetically compiled by planetary scientists.
Although Venus was probably habitable in the past -- over the course of several billion years -- it was exposed to excessive heat and ultraviolet radiation.
Its oceans evaporated and water vapor was burned by ultraviolet light.
Hydrogen escaped, leaving only a dense atmosphere of carbon dioxide with the lethal effect of a greenhouse gas -- that's Venus as we know it today.
The researchers published their results from the new Venus climate model in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
