Kepler measures the rate of star rotation in the Pleiades
The Kepler Space Telescope's latest mission to help astronomers is to obtain an almost complete list of the rotation rates of stars from the Pleiades star cluster.
The new data helps astronomers understand why stars in the cluster spin at different speeds, and how the rotation time relates to the formation of the planet.
“By comparing our results to other clusters, we hope to learn more about the relationship between stellar matter, its age and even the history of its solar system,” said Luisa Rebull, a researcher at Caltech’s Infrared Processing and Analysis Center in Pasadena.
The Pleiades star cluster is located 445 light-years from Earth.
Many of the stars in the cluster are now reaching maturity and have formed over 125 million years.
It is now turning the fastest.
In moments of maximum rotation, these teenage stars release huge amounts of stellar wind.
Because these winds move along the magnetic fields of stars, they have a slowing effect on them.
As the star ages, its rate of rotation slows.
Kepler measures the rate of rotation of each star by measuring the time between the discovery of discernible points on the stars -- similar to sunspots.
According to the latest data on rotational speeds, larger stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Rebull compares the stars to dancers, making pirouettes more slowly than smaller ones.
“In the Pleiades ‘ballet’, we see that the slower-spinning stars are more massive, while the ones that spin the fastest are usually very light stars,” Rebull said.
Because the Pleiades cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory for comparing star quality and rotational speeds.
"The Pleiades provide us with an anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation in both directions, in younger and older stars," Rebull said.
There’s still a lot to learn about how, when, and why the stars slow down their rotation speed, so to speak, “hanging their dancing shoes on a nail.”
Rebull and her colleagues detailed the latest analysis of Pleiades’ rotational speeds in three studies, which will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
Is a Qualifying Agreement Necessary?
If I did not apply, then the qualification agreement would not be concluded and after a few months I could move to another hospital?
Is it even possible to work after graduation without enrolling in specialized education?
My point is that in the field in which I would like to work, there is now a vacancy only in a somewhat more distant hospital, but in about six months there could be a vacancy in another one, where I would like to work afterwards.
I don’t know how to deal with this issue, the question continues.
Corresponds to Mgr. Lenka Vlková.
No legislation provides for the obligation to conclude a qualification agreement with an employer - a hospital.
A qualification agreement is a legal institution regulated by the Labour Code and may be concluded between an employee and an employer in order to ensure the recovery of the costs incurred in increasing or deepening the employee’s qualifications.
In the health sector, there is a long-term pressure not to conclude these agreements with a view to ensuring the labour mobility of health workers, and not all hospitals currently require this agreement.
According to Act No. 95/2004 Coll., on the conditions for obtaining and recognition of professional competence and specialized competence for the exercise of the medical profession of a doctor, dentist and pharmacist, participation in specialized education is considered to be a deepening of the qualification (not an increase of the qualification).
This means that a qualification agreement can only be concluded under the Labour Code if the costs amount to at least CZK 75,000.
No legislation or obligation to enroll in specialized education.
The law only lays down the conditions for applying for inclusion in the field of specialized education.
However, according to the law, a doctor is entitled to pursue the profession of a doctor thanks to the completion of the necessary university studies, although under the conditions laid down by law (under the professional supervision of a doctor with specialized competence in the relevant field).
The law foresees a situation in which professional practice completed in another field of specialization can be included in the specialist training of a doctor, provided that its content and scope correspond to the relevant educational program.
Theoretically, it would be possible to count the time worked elsewhere, which would correspond to the questioner's situation.
However, given that I do not know the specific circumstances of this case, consultation with the relevant department of the Ministry of Health (Department of Science and Medical Professions) can be recommended, since the Ministry of Health by law provides advisory and consulting services related to the inclusion in and the course of specialized education.
The counseling service is also provided free of charge by the Czech Medical Chamber, of which every doctor must be a member.
